One of Northern Ireland's largest homebuilders is to accept the digital currency Bitcoin.

Ballyclare-based Hagan Homes is believed to be the first firm of its kind in Northern Ireland or the Republic of Ireland to take the step.

The worldwide payment system enables peer-to-peer transactions between users without an intermediary.

Managing director Jamesy Hagan said: "Bitcoin is an innovative new payment method and essentially a new kind of money. It is very similar to a cash transaction.

"There has been a significant growth in the use of Bitcoin worldwide and our acceptance of this new channel reflects our willingness to respond to the market."

Hagan Homes recorded a turnover of more than £18 million in 2016/17 and marked its second biggest year of home completions since it was established almost 30 years ago.

A total of 207 homes across 15 sites in Northern Ireland were completed, an 8% increase on the previous year.

Mr Hagan added: "The international appeal of Northern Ireland is continuing to grow.

"There are an increasing number of international investors establishing businesses in Northern Ireland and subsequently this means that the number of people wanting to live, work or invest in Northern Ireland is increasing."

He acknowledged challenges facing the new currency.

"Of course, there are some risks to using Bitcoin for payment due to the cryptocurrency's volatility, but buyers and sellers are finding creative ways to deal with these challenges," he said.

"By incorporating the learning from our peers into our approach we can embrace this innovation."

I recently had the pleasure of visiting one of the best places to eat in Koreatown! Beer Belly is already a local legend that needs no introduction. But for the curious who are reading this online and haven't had the pleasure of visiting yet, you have come to the right place.

Choosing a place to eat in Koreatown (yes, Ktown for locals) is a challenge in and of itself. Koreatown is one of America's 24-hour cities. From Korean BBQ to Bengali cuisine, the great cultural diversity of Ktown makes eating here at any hour enjoyable.

Back to Beer Belly. No for those who may be less adventurous with their cuisine choices can go wrong with Beer Belly. It has a classic bar style menu with some really unique takes on classics like Wings and Grilled Cheese. I know, I know, how can you make grilled cheese special. You'll have to visit Beer Belly yourself and experience it first hand.

Another quirky element of their menu is the abundance of duck options. I had the Death by Duck as an appetizer which is a plate of fries covered in a scrumptious gravy and a healthy topping of duck!

Some interesting features about the location itself to also note: there is a nice covered outdoor patio space if you thinking about going during the day and want to get some fresh air. And they are also pet friendly (and we brought our little pup there with us)

Staff is very friendly and not snobby like some places like this can get so you are definitely in for an all around appetizing experience in Koreatown if you visit Beer Belly.

Disclosure notice: I am in not affiliated with Beer Belly in any way personal and they are not paying me to write this post. I am just a Koreatown local who loves my neighborhood and everything is has to offer and want to help more people understand and experience it's greatness :)
